instead of the workaround being adding docs on how to fix this, we could also just use an `8MiB` thread under the hood for the generated context code. would be a workaround for until we simplify the ACL generated code.

literally just wrap the current codegen in
```rust
{
  let thread = ::std::thread::Builder::new()
    .stack_size(8 * 1024 * 1024)
    .spawn(|| /* ... the current codegen output ... */)
    .expect("unable to create thread with 8MiB stack");

  match thread.join() {
    Ok(context) => context,
    Err(e) => panic!(
      "{}",
      e.downcast_ref::<&str>()
        .copied()
        .or_else(|| e.downcast_ref::<String>().map(|x| x.as_str()))
        .unwrap_or("the generated `Context` panicked during creation")
    ),
  }
}
```

(real code would probably grab the last `.expect` from the result and panic with that message, since that is the panic message the thread panicked with)

